# Step 1 – Add Another Controller Function

Open:

```text
backend/src/controllers/productController.js
```

Initially, the file contained only one controller function:

```javascript
const getAllProducts = (req, res) => {
    res.json({
        message: "List of products will appear here."
    });
};

module.exports = {
    getAllProducts,
};
```

A second controller function was added:

```javascript
const createProduct = (req, res) => {
    res.json({
        message: "Product created successfully!"
    });
};
```

The exports were updated:

```javascript
module.exports = {
    getAllProducts,
    createProduct,
};
```

---

# Why Export Multiple Functions?

`module.exports` makes functions available to other JavaScript files.

Previously, only one function was available:

```javascript
module.exports = {
    getAllProducts,
};
```

Now two functions are available:

```javascript
module.exports = {
    getAllProducts,
    createProduct,
};
```

Think of the controller as a toolbox.

Before:

```text
Product Controller
│
└── getAllProducts()
```

After:

```text
Product Controller
│
├── getAllProducts()
└── createProduct()
```

As the application grows, more controller functions will be added, such as:

```text
Product Controller
│
├── getAllProducts()
├── getProductById()
├── createProduct()
├── updateProduct()
└── deleteProduct()
```

