# Step 2 – Import the New Controller Function

Open:

```text
backend/src/routes/productRoutes.js
```

Originally, the file imported one function:

```javascript
const { getAllProducts } = require("../controllers/productController");
```

It was updated to import two functions:

```javascript
const {
    getAllProducts,
    createProduct,
} = require("../controllers/productController");
```

---

# Why Did We Update the Import?

The controller now exports two functions.

The routes file imports whichever controller functions it needs.

This allows the route to forward different requests to different controller functions.

---

# Step 3 – Create a POST Route

Previously, the routes file contained:

```javascript
router.get("/", getAllProducts);
```

A second route was added:

```javascript
router.post("/", createProduct);
```

The completed routes file became:

```javascript
const express = require("express");

const {
    getAllProducts,
    createProduct,
} = require("../controllers/productController");

const router = express.Router();

// GET /products
router.get("/", getAllProducts);

// POST /products
router.post("/", createProduct);

module.exports = router;
```

---

# Understanding HTTP Methods

Notice that both routes use the same URL:

```text
/products
```

The difference is the HTTP method.

| Method | URL         | Controller         |
| ------ | ----------- | ------------------ |
| GET    | `/products` | `getAllProducts()` |
| POST   | `/products` | `createProduct()`  |

Express uses both the URL and the HTTP method to determine which controller should handle the request.

